Node.Notes: There are errors in the English interlinear for this and the next word. They are simply "may they perish" and "wicked people."
Uncertain. Means "build a highway/prepare a way" in most cases, but also extol/lift up a song.
Text says "in the deserts," but most take as defective spelling for "on the clouds." In favor are texts like ps18:9-11; dt33:26; and is19:1 where the clouds are thought of as God's chariot.
Description of what happens when God goes out and marches is delayed till the next verse.
Uncertain. Some takes as "this Sinai [quaked] before God, the God of Israel." Tree assumes "This One of Sinai" in apposition to "God." See also ju5:5.
Usually translations see weary as description of inheritance (referring to the land of Canaan), so your weary inheritance/land or your inheritance/land when it is parched.
Feminine plural participle, so apparently women who carry good news (other places where women carried news of victory or defeat, are ex15:20-21; 1s18:6-7).
Uncertain exactly where the message ends between vs. 13-15.
Uncertain. Could be derived from "abode" or "beauty." Many take to refer to "she who remains at home."
Uncertain. Denunciation of those Israelites who did not go to battle but stayed behind in the safety of their homes or camps?
Uncertain. Many take to be "sheepfolds" like in ju5:16 (despite problematic spelling here).

Uncertain what "the wings of a dove are covered with silver, its pinions with green gold" means. Many proposals, though most commonly accepted is that it describes the women dividing the spoil among themselves. Also some take the dove to be a figure for Israel.
Literally, "green gold," which most take to be equivalent of shining/fine gold.

Uncertain. May be superlative "mighty/majesty mountain" or "mountain of God." In next verse, seems Mount Bashan is rebuked for its envy of Mount Zion. Some take all four np's in this verse as vocatives.
Should be to dwell/abide. English gloss as "reign" is unjustified.
Could mean mighty/magnificent chariot or chariot of God.
Uncertain. Twice ten thousand could mean twenty thousand or multiplicative sense of ten thousand times thousands of times (so a very large, indefinite number).
Uncertain, with many different proposals. Traditionally taken as repetition, so multiplication of thousands, thus thousands of thousands.
Syntax of second half of this verse uncertain. Tree assumes "the Lord [is] among them, [He is] at Sinai in the holy place."
Uncertain. See commentaries. Tree assumes: [You took captive/received] even ones rebelling so that Yahweh might dwell [with them].
Outgoings in relation to death, apparently means escape from death.

Uncertain. May be 2nd person masculine "you" or 3rd person feminine (your foot as S). Many follow ancient versions with "you will wade your foot in blood." Tree assumes "your foot will shatter [them] in blood."
Picture of dogs lapping up human blood.
Literally, "fountain/spring/source." Most take "fountain of Israel" to refer to all true Israelites.
Uncertain why these four tribes are singled out, though the first two are in the South and the last two are in the North. Translation of this verse is uncertain.
Could mean smallest or youngest.
Uncertain. Many go with leading, though meaning is more like "dominate/rule." Could be from verb meaning "fall into trance/deep sleep," which some take to mean "is in an ecstatic trance."
Uncertain. May be heap, in the sense of a heap/throng of people.
Uncertain what "your God has ordered your strength" means. "Your" presumably refers to Israel.
Syntax and meaning of entire verse very uncertain.
Many different proposals about identities of animals and the referents for them. The most likely referent is probably Egypt, though any foe of Israel that loves war and plunder might be possible.
Maybe calves, that is/consisting of, people.
From verb meaning "to disturb water/to make muddy," which many take in sense of to trample and others to humble.
Uncertain. Many take as bars/pieces.
To hurry its hands, which may mean to bring tribute in haste. Many translate obscurely as "Cush hastens to stretch out her hands to God."
